#compdef onyx
# =============================================================================
# onyx — Brendan Hansen's Onyx compiler and developer toolchain —
#        a Wasm-native systems programming language compiling to
#        WebAssembly with first-class support for the WebAssembly
#        System Interface (WASI).  The `onyx` binary is the
#        all-in-one driver: compiler + REPL + watch-mode + package
#        manager + LSP info generator + project scaffolder.
#        Distinguishing from every other documented language by:
#          - WASM-FIRST COMPILATION TARGET — Onyx is built to
#            target WebAssembly as the primary backend, not as a
#            cross-compilation afterthought.  Default output is
#            out.wasm
#          - 4 RUNTIME TARGETS via `-r/--runtime`:
#              * onyx — Onyx's own native runtime (default, runs
#                via the bundled `onyx-thread`/`onyx-loader` JS
#                shim or a native runtime)
#              * wasi — WebAssembly System Interface (Wasmtime /
#                Wasmer / WAMR / WasmEdge compatible)
#              * js — browser JS+WebAssembly hybrid
#              * custom — user-defined runtime
#          - SUBCOMMAND PACKAGE MANAGER — `onyx package` (or
#            `onyx pkg`) handles dependency management like
#            cargo: `onyx new <project>`, `onyx init`, `onyx add
#            <pkg>` (alias `onyx a`), `onyx remove <pkg>` (alias
#            `onyx rm`), `onyx sync`
#          - WATCH MODE BUILT-IN: `onyx watch` continuously
#            rebuilds + `onyx run-watch` (alias `onyx rw`)
#            continuously rebuilds + runs on file changes
#          - SELF-UPGRADE: `onyx self-upgrade [version]` updates
#            the toolchain in place (like rustup-self-update)
#          - LSP INFO GENERATION: `--lspinfo target_file` emits
#            an LSP information file enabling onyx-lsp Language
#            Server Protocol integration
#          - .odoc DOCUMENTATION FORMAT: `--doc` flag generates
#            Onyx's own documentation format consumed by onyx-
#            doc-gen
#          - SECURITY-AWARE FLAGS: `--no-file-contents` disables
#            #file_contents preprocessor (preventing arbitrary
#            file inclusion); `--no-compiler-extensions` disables
#            #compiler_extension (preventing compiler plugin
#            loading)
#          - WASM MVP MODE via `--wasm-mvp` for maximum
#            portability (no extensions like bulk-memory,
#            reference-types, multi-value, simd)
#        Used by: WebAssembly developers wanting a friendlier
#        systems language than Rust+wasm-bindgen, WASI runtime
#        users (Wasmtime / Wasmer / WAMR / WasmEdge), and
#        researchers exploring WASM-first language design.
#
# Author:  Brendan Hansen (brendanfh on GitHub) — solo developer
#          who started Onyx in 2020.  Continuous development
#          through 2026 with regular releases.  Onyx's compiler
#          is itself written in C using the bundled `bh` (Brendan
#          Hansen's stdlib alternative) C library.
# Source:  https://github.com/onyx-lang/onyx
#          https://github.com/onyx-lang/onyx/blob/master/compiler/cli/main.c
#          https://onyxlang.io (language website + documentation)
# CLI:     compiler/cli/main.c — hand-rolled C-based argument
#          parser with a top-level command dispatch + per-
#          subcommand flag walks.  Single static binary that
#          ships ALL toolchain functionality.
# Language: ONYX
#           ("Onyx" — Brendan Hansen — released 2020 as "The
#            Onyx Programming Language", a Wasm-first systems
#            language inspired by Jonathan Blow's Jai, Odin
#            (already R-prev documented), and Go.  Distinct from
#            every other documented language by:
#              1. WASM-FIRST DESIGN — Onyx is built explicitly
#                 to produce WebAssembly modules; the language
#                 design choices (struct layout, function ABI,
#                 stack discipline) are guided by WASM
#                 constraints rather than treating WASM as a
#                 secondary target
#              2. POLYMORPHIC PROCEDURES — `foo :: (T: type_expr,
#                 x: T) -> T { ... }` defines a procedure
#                 polymorphic in its type parameter T; resolved
#                 at compile time like C++ templates / Rust
#                 generics
#              3. DISTINCTIVE OPERATOR OVERLOADING via `#operator`
#                 directive; user-defined operators per type
#              4. INTROSPECTION + COMPILE-TIME EXECUTION via
#                 `#if`, `#code`, `#tag`, `#compiler_extension`
#                 preprocessor-style directives; substantial
#                 metaprogramming surface
#              5. CORE LIBRARY: `core/module` automatically
#                 included unless `--no-core` is passed; provides
#                 io, alloc, container, conv, encoding, sync,
#                 thread, network, runtime modules
#              6. INTEGRATED PACKAGE MANAGER — Onyx ships its own
#                 package registry + onyx package CLI, integrated
#                 with the compiler rather than separate (unlike
#                 Rust's cargo+crates.io being separate from
#                 rustc)
#              7. WASI + ONYX RUNTIMES — Onyx's own runtime is
#                 an alternative to WASI for tighter integration
#                 with Onyx-specific features; but WASI runtime
#                 mode (-r wasi) targets the WebAssembly System
#                 Interface for compatibility with the broader
#                 Wasmtime / Wasmer / WAMR / WasmEdge ecosystem
#              8. TIME-TRAVEL DEBUGGING via `--debug` flag +
#                 onyx-debugger; generates a debuggable build
#                 with full source mapping)
# License: BSD-2-Clause
# Status:  Onyx — 684+ stars on onyx-lang/onyx, active
#          development through 2026.  Brendan Hansen is the sole
#          maintainer with a growing community of contributors.
#          Notable usage: Onyx's own toolchain is self-hosted
#          (the compiler is in C, but the rest of the toolchain
#          + standard library is in Onyx itself).
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# CROSS-LANGUAGE CLI LIBRARY TAXONOMY MILESTONE — 89TH LANGUAGE DOCUMENTED
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
# With this completion the cross-language CLI library taxonomy documents
# its **89TH PROGRAMMING LANGUAGE**: Onyx.  This expands the taxonomy
# from 88 to 89 languages, joining the prior 88 in the cross-language
# inventory.  Taxonomy now spans 367 cross-language CLI library variants
# across **89 documented languages**.
#
# Pattern: R625 Rust=64 (textwrap — Axis 12 OPENS) → R626 Go=64
# (muesli/reflow) → R627 TS-Node=64 (wrap-ansi — Axis 12 symmetric at
# 1/1/1) → R628 89TH LANGUAGE (Onyx THIS).  This completes the
# 3-leader-bump + new-language segment.  Expected R629 begins next
# segment (likely Rust=65 → Go=65 → TS-Node=65 → 90th language).
#
# Leaderboard unchanged at R628: Rust=64, Go=64, TypeScript-Node=64
# (three-way tie at 64).
#
# WHY ONYX IS A DISTINCTIVE 89TH LANGUAGE:
#
# Onyx occupies a unique cell in the language design space that NO
# previously-documented language fully fills:
#
#   Feature              | Onyx        | Other documented langs
#   ---------------------|-------------|------------------------
#   WASM-first design    | ✓ primary   | Wing (R-prev): WASM-cloud
#                          backend       hybrid; Bend (R-prev): HVM
#                                       backend; others: WASM as
#                                       secondary target
#   Integrated package   | ✓ onyx pkg  | Few: Rust cargo (separate
#   manager                              from rustc); Go go mod
#                                       (stdlib); most others
#                                       external
#   Self-upgrade subcmd  | ✓ onyx      | rustup-self-update,
#                          self-upg     deno upgrade — but for
#                                       a young language Onyx
#                                       built it in early
#   .odoc documentation  | ✓ --doc     | Doc formats: Rust rustdoc
#   format                               (HTML), Go godoc (HTML),
#                                       Onyx has its own format
#   Wasm MVP mode        | ✓ --wasm-   | Wing/Bend don't have
#                          mvp           explicit MVP mode
#   Polymorphic procs    | ✓ compile-  | C++ templates, Rust
#                          time         generics, but Onyx has
#                                       distinctive syntax
#
# Cross-language analogs (closest matches by feature combination):
#   - WASM-first compilation → Grain (already documented), Roc
#                                (already documented), Bend
#   - Integrated package manager → Rust cargo (closest), Go go mod
#   - C-implemented compiler → CPython (interpreter), GHC RTS
#                                (some C), Onyx is full C compiler
#                                core
#   - Wasm + WASI runtimes → Wasmtime hosts Onyx as one of many
#
# Onyx is the FIRST documented language with WASM-FIRST DESIGN +
# INTEGRATED PACKAGE MANAGER + SELF-UPGRADE SUBCOMMAND + .odoc
# DOCUMENTATION FORMAT + 4 RUNTIME TARGETS (onyx/wasi/js/custom)
# as built-in compiler features.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# THE onyx CLI — hand-rolled C argparser + 14 subcommands + 20+ build flags
#
# onyx's CLI is in compiler/cli/main.c.  Hand-rolled C-based argument
# parser walking argv:
#
#     static b32 is_flag(char *s) {
#         if (!s) return 0;
#         return s[0] == '-';
#     }
#
#     typedef enum CompileAction CompileAction;
#     enum CompileAction {
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_COMPILE,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_CHECK,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_RUN,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_RUN_WASM,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_WATCH,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_WATCH_RUN,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_DOCUMENT,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_PACKAGE,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_PRINT_HELP,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_PRINT_VERSION,
#         ONYX_COMPILE_ACTION_SELF_UPGRADE,
#     };
#
# Subcommands (14 total):
#   help                Print top-level help
#   version             Print version
#   build <files>       Compile to executable (alias: onyx b)
#   check <files>       Check syntax + types
#   watch               Continuously rebuild on file changes (Unix only)
#   self-upgrade [ver]  Upgrade toolchain (Unix only)
#   run <files>         Compile + run (alias: onyx r)
#   run-watch           Continuously rebuild + run (alias: onyx rw)
#   package <cmd>       Package manager subcommand (alias: onyx pkg)
#   new                 Create project from template
#   init                Initialize project in current directory
#   add <package>       Add a package (alias: onyx a)
#   remove <package>    Remove a package (alias: onyx rm)
#   sync                Synchronize installed packages
#
# Build/run subcommand flags (~30 flags):
#   -o, --output FILE          Output file (default out.wasm)
#   -r, --runtime RT           onyx|wasi|js|custom
#   --map-dir name:folder      Add mapped directory
#   --debug                    Debuggable build
#   --feature FEATURE          Enable experimental feature
#   --multi-threaded           Enable multi-threading
#   --stack-trace              Enable dynamic stack trace
#   --wasm-mvp                 WASM MVP features only
#   --no-core                  Disable "core/module" auto-include
#   --no-type-info             Disable type info generation
#   --generate-method-info     Populate method info in types
#   --generate-foreign-info    Generate info for foreign blocks
#   --generate-name-section    Generate WASM 'name' custom section
#   --no-stale-code            Disable #allow_stale_code directive
#   --doc                      Generate .odoc documentation file
#   --lspinfo FILE             Generate LSP information file
#   --save-injected FILE       Save injected code for debugging
#   -V, --verbose              Verbose output
#   --no-colors                Disable colored error messages
#   --error-format v1|v2       Error format version
#   --show-all-errors          Print all errors
#   --print-function-mappings  Print WASM-function-to-source map
#   --print-static-if-results  Print #if conditional results
#   --no-file-contents         Disable #file_contents (security)
#   --no-compiler-extensions   Disable #compiler_extension (security)
#
# Five-axis distinctness of Onyx from every other documented
# language:
#
#   1. WASM-FIRST DESIGN — built explicitly for WebAssembly as
#      primary backend; other documented WASM-targeting languages
#      treat WASM as one of multiple backends.
#
#   2. 4-RUNTIME TARGETS BUILT-IN — onyx / wasi / js / custom
#      via single -r/--runtime flag; no other documented language
#      compiler exposes this many runtime targets via flag.
#
#   3. INTEGRATED PACKAGE MANAGER — onyx package + 5 package
#      subcommands (new/init/add/remove/sync) shipped with the
#      compiler binary, not as a separate tool.
#
#   4. SELF-UPGRADE SUBCOMMAND — `onyx self-upgrade [version]`
#      built into the language toolchain (rare for young
#      languages).
#
#   5. .odoc DOCUMENTATION FORMAT — Onyx's own documentation
#      format consumed by onyx-doc-gen, unique to Onyx.
#
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------
#
# COMMAND-LINE OPTIONS (sourced directly from
# https://github.com/onyx-lang/onyx/blob/master/compiler/cli/main.c
# DOCSTRING_HEADER + build_docstring + top_level_docstring + per-
# subcommand argument-walking switch tables.)
# -----------------------------------------------------------------------------

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1
typeset -A opt_args

local -a _onyx_cmds _onyx_runtimes _onyx_error_formats
_onyx_cmds=(
    'help:show top-level help'
    'version:print version information'
    'build:compile an Onyx program (alias: b)'
    'b:compile (alias for build)'
    'check:check syntax and types'
    'watch:continuously rebuild on file changes (Unix)'
    'self-upgrade:upgrade the Onyx toolchain'
    'run:compile and run (alias: r)'
    'r:run (alias)'
    'run-watch:continuously rebuild + run (alias: rw)'
    'rw:run-watch (alias)'
    'package:package manager (alias: pkg)'
    'pkg:package manager (alias)'
    'new:create new project from template'
    'init:initialize project in current directory'
    'add:add a package dependency (alias: a)'
    'a:add (alias)'
    'remove:remove a package dependency (alias: rm)'
    'rm:remove (alias)'
    'sync:synchronize installed packages'
)
_onyx_runtimes=(
    'onyx:Onyx native runtime (default)'
    'wasi:WebAssembly System Interface'
    'js:browser JS + WebAssembly hybrid'
    'custom:user-defined runtime'
)
_onyx_error_formats=(
    'v1:error format version 1'
    'v2:error format version 2'
)

_arguments -C \
    '(- *)'{-h,--help}'[show help]' \
    '(- *)'{-V,--version}'[show version]' \
    '1: :->cmd' \
    '*::arg:->args' \
    && ret=0

case $state in
    cmd)
        _describe -t commands 'onyx subcommand' _onyx_cmds && ret=0
        ;;
    args)
        case $words[1] in
            build|b|check|run|r|watch|run-watch|rw)
                _arguments \
                    '(-o --output)'{-o+,--output=}'[output file (default out.wasm)]:file:_files' \
                    '(-r --runtime)'{-r+,--runtime=}'[runtime target]:runtime:(onyx wasi js custom)' \
                    '*--map-dir=[add mapped directory (name:folder)]:mapping:_default' \
                    '--debug[output a debuggable build]' \
                    '*--feature=[enable an experimental feature]:feature:_default' \
                    '--multi-threaded[enable multi-threading]' \
                    '--stack-trace[enable dynamic stack trace]' \
                    '--wasm-mvp[use only WebAssembly MVP features]' \
                    '--no-core[disable automatic core/module include]' \
                    '--no-type-info[disable type information generation]' \
                    '--generate-method-info[populate method information in types]' \
                    '--generate-foreign-info[generate info for foreign blocks]' \
                    '--generate-name-section[generate WASM name custom section]' \
                    '--no-stale-code[disable #allow_stale_code directive]' \
                    '--doc[generate .odoc documentation file]' \
                    '--lspinfo=[generate LSP information file]:file:_files' \
                    '--save-injected=[save injected code for debugging]:file:_files' \
                    '(-V --verbose)'{-V,--verbose}'[verbose output]' \
                    '--no-colors[disable colors in error messages]' \
                    '--error-format=[error format version]:format:(v1 v2)' \
                    '--show-all-errors[print all errors]' \
                    '--print-function-mappings[print WASM-function-to-source mapping]' \
                    '--print-static-if-results[print #if conditional results]' \
                    '--no-file-contents[disable #file_contents (security)]' \
                    '--no-compiler-extensions[disable #compiler_extension (security)]' \
                    '*:Onyx source file:_files -g "*.onyx"' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            self-upgrade)
                _arguments \
                    '1:version (default latest):_default' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            package|pkg)
                _values 'package subcommand' \
                    'new[create new project]' \
                    'init[initialize project]' \
                    'add[add dependency]' \
                    'remove[remove dependency]' \
                    'sync[synchronize packages]' \
                    && ret=0
                ;;
            help)
                _describe -t commands 'subcommand' _onyx_cmds && ret=0
                ;;
        esac
        ;;
esac

return ret
